/li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> Palestinian physicians</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> are trained</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">at the Hadassah</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> campus</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> in Jerusalem, </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">and quickly gain t</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">he tools to bring the highest level of care available to patients in their </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">own </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">communities. They live at home and come to train daily at Hadassah, but in parallel </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">they also begin to integrate into the Palestinian medical health-care system. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">Over the years, t</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">he training of these doctors at Hadassah has made a major contribution to the advancement of medicine in the West Bank and Gaza and to the development of medic</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">al specialties which were not previously available such as Dermatology, Endocrinology, Hematology, Radiology, Anesthesiology, ENT, Gynecology and Neurosurgery. One doctor who specialized in Neurosurgery went on to head the Neurosurgery Department at the Be</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">it Jalla Hospital; another physician who specialized in Neurology is one of the most prominent physicians in the West Bank</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> in his field</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">; the Director of the Hebron Hospital specialized in Gynecology at Hadassah; and two neurosurgeons are presently working </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">other</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> West Bank</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> Medical Centers</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">. Today, the Head of Dermatological Medicine in the Palestinian Authority - who is also the Chairman of the Palestinian Society for Dermatology - is doing a two year special </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">fellowship</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> at Hadassah, and he comes to Jerusale</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">m from Ramallah for two days each week.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">Palestinian physicians who have trained at Hadassah have formed warm relationships with </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">their colleagues and</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> often return after their training to participate in Departmental meetings, to present problematic pati</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">ents, have the opportunity to hear what is going on in the department and, most importantly, keep abreast of </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">new developments in their field of expertise</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 1.05pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">The following examples – just two of many - exemplify the vital importance </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">th</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">e results of the on</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">going </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">collaboration</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> between Hadassah </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">physicians </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">and its Palestinian counterparts. The</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">ir joint </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">ultimate goal is</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">to fight the disease</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">to save and improve lives</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">A Palestinian </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">physician in his last year of </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">residen</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">cy</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> at Hadassah in the field of pediatric car</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">diology, regularly receives requests for consultations from hospitals across the West Bank. He has </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">also</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> opened his own clinic in Ramallah where he sees young patients.</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> So for three days a week he travels across the West Bank and sees patients in his clinic and</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">or the rest of the week, he continues to train in his department at Hadassah. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">This cross-border reality has been very beneficial for the critical infants this </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">resident treats. Not too long ago he examined a critically ill infant and concluded that her only chance for survival was to be taken to Hadassah. He immediately presented the case to his colleagues at the hospital and everyone together decided, without he</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">sitation, that the baby should be brought in immediately. A bed was made available in the Pediatric Intensive Care Unit and with necessary facilitation the baby was brought across the check-point to the hospital</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> with her father</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">. The baby underwent an ultra</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">sound examination to see if she could undergo</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">catheterization.  When it was determined she could, a catheterization procedure was </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">carried out immediately</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> At some stage in the near future, the goal is to be able to have the knowledge and tools to carry out</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> this procedure at his new clinic.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">Another example is the</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> Cystic Fibrosis Center in Gaza</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> which was opened by one of the Palestinian Physicians which trained in out Pediatric Center for Chronic Diseases.</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">There used to be a time that</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> Hadassah’s CF Center tr</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">eated dozens of young patients from Gaza since there was</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">no</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">CF</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">specialist</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> there. When politics prevented these patients from coming to Israel, some traveled to Cairo to undergo CF treatments there – a 12-hour trip – but this soon became difficult, and the</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">n impossible. The parents of these chronically sick children turned to the international community for help in establishing a CF Center in Gaza. Together with Hadassah, a 1-year comprehensive training program was launched for three Palestinian physicians a</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">nd practical training was provided for a nurse, a nutritionist, and a physiotherapist. Upon completion of their training, they returned to the Gaza Strip to establish an advanced CF Center. Ongoing communications with our own Center continues and an active</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt"> professional relationship for the benefit of patients still exists. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">HMO strongly believes that British Aid could be allocated in a manner that would be instrumental in helping promote peace efforts and coexistence, by supporting collaborative Israeli-Palestinian projects and programs such as the ones carried out by Hadassa</span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">h, to benefit all its participants. </span><span style="font-family:Sylfaen; font-size:12pt">We will be happy to further elaborate in writing or orally to the committee and are honored that you have approached us to contribute to this important debate. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 1.05pt 0pt 45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><div style="width:auto; height:auto; float:left;"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>